Non-Communicable Diseases, Eight Key Points
GENÈVE - Non-Communicable Diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, stroke, cancer, diabetes and chronic respiratory diseases are responsible for 70 % of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, sedentary lifestyle, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It is in this context that non-communicable diseases alliances networks convened from December 9 to 11 at the second World Forum of the Non-Communicable Diseases Alliance in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to address NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the HIV/AIDS movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress made.
Although the battle is not over, HIV/AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs can reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as being in a state of « semi-comatose » waiting for « an electric shock. » He added: « But who will have the courage to administer it? »
We believe there are lessons to be learned from the activists fighting against HIV/AIDS.
As global attention focuses on the prevention of NCDs, those seeking to tackle avoidable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC of HIV/AIDS advocacy organizations.
The first letter that the NCD community must consider is « A », as in activism.
Anyone over the age of 40 surely remembers the images of HIV/AIDS activists participating in « die-ins » during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, HIV/AIDS activists took to the streets, even closing down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
On a global scale, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the « B » of the HIV/AIDS movement's strategy.
Civil organisation and grassroots activism can mobilise the first energies, but the organisation and maintenance of a broad coalition needs money.
The HIV/AIDS movement was clear about this from the beginning and pressured for resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: the HIV/AIDS movements did not hesitate to understand that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing rights.
Alliances and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from public authorities, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The HIV/AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.
Thus, « D », the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: as many factors that played a driving role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
MNT are no less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - « E » - was what helped the HIV/AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which defended the slogan « Nothing about us without us », HIV/AIDS advocates demanded the representation of existing bodies to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Governing Council intended for representatives of civil society.
This norm is so deeply embedded in the HIV/AIDS movement that it would be almost unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and « F » - framing the issue - is essential for the HIV/AIDS community to gain the support of political leaders.
Particularly, access to HIV treatment has been presented as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the narrative in this way leads to a significant reduction in the price of medicines, to the extent that over half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the issue for HIV/AIDS, a very relevant issue for the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV/AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on the lifestyle choices of individuals, rather than on attributing responsibility to the state for healthcare provision and the removal of legal discrimination.
In the debate on HIV/AIDS, gender - the « G » of our movement - has been a significant issue.
HIV was initially considered as a « disease of gays », and gender identity was embedded from the beginning in the DNA of the HIV/AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focus of prevention efforts for NCDs.
Finally, « H » - human rights - are the foundation of the response to HIV/AIDS.
Campaigns were launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools and in medical centers.
The strategic dispute allowed for equality under the law to be ensured.
The HIV/AIDS movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The NCD movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue through the alphabet the list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but it seems appropriate to close it on « H », given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk for HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: « Why don't these people make better choices? » The AIDS fight movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70 % of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, « these people » represent a large number of us.
The communities of NCDs and HIV/AIDS can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
